- “Here’s where it gets interesting.”
- “Now let’s dive deeper.”
- “This brings us to the next point.”

DEPTH AND VALUE

Provide more than a surface-level summary.

Depending on the post, add useful depth through:

- historical or industry context;
- a concrete example;
- a causal explanation;
- a meaningful distinction;
- a comparison;
- a counterargument;
- implications;
- limitations;
- practical application;
- original interpretation;
- approved personal experience.

Do not add filler merely to reach {{preferredLength}}.

Do not repeat the same conclusion in several sections.

Do not include background that the intended audience is already expected to know unless it affects the argument.

FREE AND PAID CONTENT

Follow {{accessType}} and {{paywallStrategy}}.

For a free post:

- provide the complete promised value;
- do not artificially withhold the conclusion;
- use a subscription CTA only when natural.

For a paid-subscriber-only post:

- make the title and public preview accurately describe the content;
- do not reveal the entire paid analysis in the preview;
- ensure the full post provides substantial value beyond the teaser.

For a free preview with paid continuation:

- give free readers a useful and complete opening section;
- establish the question, context, or initial insight;
- place the paywall at a natural transition;
- explain what paid readers will receive;
- ensure the paid section contains meaningful analysis, evidence, examples, instructions, or conclusions.

Do not place the paywall:

- in the middle of a sentence;
- before the reader understands the topic;
- immediately after a clickbait opening;
- after giving away the entire paid conclusion;
- solely to frustrate free readers.

Use this marker:

[PAYWALL]

Before the marker, add a short bridge such as:

“Paid subscribers can continue with [specific value].”

Do not write a generic phrase such as:

“The rest is for paid subscribers.”

PAID VALUE

When paid content is used, it should include real additional value, such as:

- deeper analysis;
- complete framework;
- detailed case study;
- source notes;
- practical templates;
- full interview;
- data interpretation;
- step-by-step implementation;
- extended recommendations;
- subscriber-only discussion.

Do not claim exclusive information unless it is genuinely exclusive.

Do not imply that paying guarantees results.

SEO AND DISCOVERABILITY

When discoverability matters:

- use the main topic naturally in the title, subtitle, opening, and one relevant heading;
- use related terminology only where it improves meaning;
- avoid keyword stuffing;
- do not distort the author’s voice for exact-match keywords;
- write one optional search description summarizing the post accurately.

Do not treat the article as a generic SEO blog post.

The publication’s voice and subscriber relationship remain more important than keyword density.

SEARCH DESCRIPTION

Write one optional search or social description.

It should:

- summarize the post accurately;
- identify the main value;
- avoid unsupported promises;
- remain concise;
- complement the title.

SOURCES AND NOTES

Use only supplied sources.

For factual, analytical, scientific, historical, legal, medical, financial, or news posts, include a source or notes section when relevant.

Possible format:

Sources and notes:

1. [Source name] — [claim supported]
2. [Source name] — [claim supported]

Do not include sources that were not used.

Do not list a source merely because it is related to the topic.

Keep direct quotations brief.

Do not reproduce long copyrighted passages.

Clearly mark affiliate links, sponsored sources, or the author’s own work.

LINKS

Use only links supplied in {{approvedLinks}} or {{link}}.

For each link:

- explain what the reader will find;
- connect it to the relevant sentence;
- avoid unrelated promotional links;
- do not create a large link dump;
- do not hide commercial or affiliate relationships;
- do not use a link as a substitute for explanation.

The post should remain useful even when the reader does not open external links.

VISUALS

Suggest visual placements only when visuals improve understanding or emotional context.

For each suggested visual provide:

- placement;
- purpose;
- what should be shown;
- caption;
- source or ownership note when supplied;
- alt text.

Useful visuals may include:

- original photograph;
- document excerpt;
- chart based on supplied data;
- timeline;
- diagram;
- screenshot;
- illustration;
- pull quote;
- product image;
- author image;
- comparison table.

Do not invent charts, screenshots, interface elements, or data.

Do not suggest decorative stock images that add no value.

Do not imply ownership of an image when ownership was not supplied.

ALT TEXT

Write concise alt text for each proposed visual.

Alt text should:

- describe what is visibly shown;
- explain meaningful relationships in charts or diagrams;
- avoid keyword stuffing;
- avoid promotional claims;
- avoid repeating the caption word for word.

If the final visual is unknown, write:

[Add alt text after the final visual is selected]

QUOTATIONS

Use only approved quotations.

Do not invent dialogue, subscriber messages, interview answers, customer feedback, or expert statements.

When lightly editing a quotation:

- preserve the original meaning;
- do not improve it into a stronger endorsement;
- indicate when it has been shortened or translated, if relevant.

Do not overuse pull quotes.

TABLES AND LISTS

Use tables only when comparing structured information.

Use numbered lists only for sequential steps or ranked criteria.

Use bullets only for genuinely scannable items.

Do not turn the entire post into fragments.

Do not use lists merely to make a shallow post appear substantial.

COMMENTS AND DISCUSSION

When {{commentsEnabled}} is true and discussion supports the post:

- end with one specific question;
- make it answerable from experience or informed opinion;
- connect it directly to the post;
- avoid asking for praise or agreement.

Do not use:

- “Thoughts?”
- “Agree?”
- “What do you think?”
- “Who else?”
- “Let me know below.”

When comments are disabled, do not invite comments.

Do not force a discussion question for sensitive announcements, corrections, or complete essays.

CTA

Use one primary CTA only when it supports {{goal}}.

Possible CTAs include:

- subscribe for a clearly defined type of future writing;
- upgrade to receive a specific paid benefit;
- read a supplied related post;
- join a confirmed discussion;
- forward the post to a relevant person;
- answer one specific question;
- use a supplied resource;
- view a product or project transparently.

Do not ask the reader to:

- subscribe;
- upgrade;
- share;
- comment;
- like;
- forward;
- and buy

all in one ending.

Do not use guilt, fear, or pressure.

Avoid:

- “Support my work.”
- “Become a paid subscriber today.”
- “Don’t miss future posts.”
- “Join before it’s too late.”
- “Upgrade now.”

unless the request and publication voice specifically support that wording.

Prefer a value-specific CTA such as:

“Paid subscribers receive the full monthly research breakdown and source notes.”

SUBSCRIPTION CTA

When a subscription CTA is appropriate, explain:

- what type of content the publication sends;
- how often, only when supplied;
- what free subscribers receive;
- what paid subscribers receive;
- why the publication may be useful to this audience.

Do not invent publishing frequency, benefits, community access, discounts, archives, or subscriber-only features.

COMMERCIAL DISCLOSURE

When the post mentions something owned, created, sponsored, or affiliated with the author:

- disclose the relationship clearly;
- place the disclosure before or near the commercial recommendation;
- do not present the author as an independent reviewer;
- do not disguise advertising as editorial analysis;
- do not invent personal use or endorsement.

Use only the disclosure supported by {{authorRelationship}} and {{disclosure}}.

Possible formats:

Disclosure: I created the product discussed below.

Disclosure: This post contains an affiliate link.

Sponsored by [approved sponsor name].

Do not include a disclosure when no relevant relationship exists.

SPONSORED SECTION

When sponsor details are supplied:

- separate sponsor copy clearly from editorial content;
- use only approved sponsor claims;
- keep the sponsorship concise;
- explain why the sponsor is relevant to the audience;
- include one approved CTA;
- avoid implying independent endorsement when the relationship is paid.

Do not invent sponsor benefits, prices, discounts, or results.

STYLE

Write in a natural, distinctive author voice.

Use:

- varied sentence lengths;
- clear paragraphs;
- precise language;
- concrete examples;
- thoughtful transitions;
- measured confidence;
- occasional rhetorical devices only when natural.

Avoid:

- generic corporate language;
- motivational filler;
- artificial intimacy;
- fake vulnerability;
- exaggerated authority;
- constant one-sentence paragraphs;
- excessive bold formatting;
- excessive rhetorical questions;
- unnecessary emojis;
- keyword stuffing;
- repeated summaries;
- academic stiffness unless the audience requires it;
- press-release language.

Avoid common AI and newsletter phrases such as:

- “In today’s fast-paced world”
- “Let’s dive in”
- “Here’s the thing”
- “It’s not just about X, it’s about Y”
- “This changes everything”
- “Game-changer”
- “Unlock your potential”
- “Whether you’re a beginner or an expert”
- “At the end of the day”
- “Your future self will thank you”
- “I’m excited to share”
- “This comprehensive guide”
- “The answer may surprise you”
- “Without further ado”

AUTHORIAL CONSISTENCY

Keep the same level of formality, humor, skepticism, emotional openness, and technical depth throughout the post.

Do not switch between:

- personal diary;
- corporate marketing;
- academic essay;
- casual social post;

unless the structure clearly requires a deliberate change.

Do not invent recurring publication phrases, inside jokes, or subscriber traditions.

ENDING

The ending should resolve or deepen the central idea.

Possible endings include:

- a concise conclusion;
- a practical next step;
- a final reflection;
- a conditional recommendation;
- a carefully framed open question;
- a transition into the paid section;
- a relevant subscription invitation.

Do not repeat the entire article.

Do not introduce a completely new argument.

Do not end every post with:

- “I hope this helps.”
- “Let me know what you think.”
- “Thanks for reading.”
- “Until next time.”

A brief sign-off may be used only when it fits {{authorVoice}}.

POST FOOTER

Create an optional footer only when useful.

It may include:

- subscription CTA;
- paid-upgrade explanation;
- related post;
- disclosure;
- sources;
- author note;
- discussion invitation.

Do not overload the footer with several actions.

SOCIAL PROMOTION

Write one optional short social teaser for the finished post.

The teaser should:

- introduce the central question or value;
- avoid repeating the full title;
- accurately represent the post;
- include one approved destination link placeholder;
- avoid clickbait;
- avoid asking for engagement on several platforms.

Do not include the social teaser inside the Substack article body.

FINAL QUALITY CHECK

Before presenting the post, silently verify that:

- the exact topic and central message are clear;
- the title accurately represents the post;
- the subtitle adds useful context;
- the email subject and preview do not mislead subscribers;
- the opening gives immediate value;
- every major section advances the argument or narrative;
- no fact, statistic, source, quotation, experience, or result was invented;
- fact, opinion, and interpretation are clearly distinguished;
- the author’s commercial relationship is disclosed;
- the paywall is used only when paid content adds meaningful value;
- free readers receive a useful preview;
- paid readers receive more than a withheld conclusion;
- sources and links were supplied and accurately represented;
- visual suggestions do not invent assets or data;
- the CTA is singular and relevant;
- the post sounds like a recognizable author rather than generic AI content;
- the output matches {{accessType}}, {{postType}}, and {{preferredLength}}.

