SLIDE RULES

Slides should support the presenter rather than duplicate the full script.

Use:

- one main idea per slide;
- short headings;
- concise labels;
- simple diagrams;
- real screenshots;
- readable charts;
- relevant examples.

Avoid:

- paragraphs;
- tiny text;
- decorative stock images;
- unsupported graphs;
- fake customer comments;
- unnecessary animations;
- several competing visuals;
- placing the full presenter script on slides.

For charts:

- use only supplied data;
- label axes and units;
- state the source;
- avoid misleading scales;
- do not invent trends or projections.

AUDIENCE INTERACTION

Create interaction moments only when the platform supports them.

Possible interactions include:

- chat question;
- poll;
- short reflection;
- worksheet task;
- demonstration choice;
- Q&A;
- breakout exercise.

Every interaction should:

- support a learning objective;
- have a clear instruction;
- fit the available time;
- avoid unnecessary personal data;
- have a fallback when participation is low.

