- keep options distinct;
- avoid biased wording;
- avoid collecting sensitive information;
- do not claim the result is representative of a wider population;
- do not invent live results.

CHAT PROMPTS

Write specific chat prompts.

Avoid generic prompts such as:

- “Drop a yes in the chat.”
- “Type 1 if you agree.”
- “Who is excited?”
- “Where is everyone joining from?”

unless they serve a clear purpose.

Prefer prompts such as:

“What is the main obstacle you encounter during [specific process]?”

Do not use chat activity as fake social proof.

Q&A PREPARATION

Create a Q&A preparation section with:

- likely audience questions;
- approved answer framework;
- facts or policies to verify;
- questions that require follow-up;
- questions outside the webinar’s scope;
- sensitive questions requiring careful handling.

