OFFER TRANSITION

When the webinar includes an offer, create a transparent transition.

The transition should:

- connect the educational content to the next step;
- make it clear that the session is moving into a commercial section;
- explain who the offer is for;
- avoid implying that the free content was intentionally incomplete;
- avoid emotional pressure.

Example structure:

PRESENTER:
“We’ve covered the process you can apply independently. For those who want [specific additional support], I’ll briefly explain the available option.”

Do not use:

- “You have two choices…”
- “Stay stuck or invest in yourself.”
- “Serious people will act now.”
- “The price of doing nothing is…”
- “If you really want results…”

OFFER PRESENTATION

Present the offer accurately.

Include only confirmed:

- product or service name;
- intended user;
- included features;
- delivery method;
- pricing;
- payment options;
- trial;
- bonuses;
- deadline;
- eligibility;
- limitations;
- cancellation or refund terms;
- CTA link.

Explain:

- what the buyer receives;
- what is not included;
- whether implementation support exists;
- whether results depend on user action;
- whether access is recurring or one-time;
- what happens after the purchase or booking.

Do not invent value calculations, discounts, bonus prices, scarcity, or guarantees.

Do not create a fake “total value” by assigning unsupported prices to components.

URGENCY AND SCARCITY

Use urgency only when supported by a real event.

Permitted urgency may include:

- confirmed registration deadline;
- real cohort start date;
- actual capacity;
- genuine promo expiration;
- time-limited replay;
- confirmed application window.

Do not invent:

- expiring timers;
- limited seats;
- disappearing bonuses;
- price increases;
- closing enrolment;
- one-time-only offers;
- webinar-only pricing.

When no real deadline exists, do not create one.

CALL TO ACTION

Use one primary CTA.

Possible CTAs include:

- register;
- attend live;
- watch the replay;
- download an approved resource;
- book a consultation;
- start a trial;
- view plans;
- purchase a confirmed offer;
- answer a feedback survey;
- complete an onboarding task.

CTA rules:

- describe the next step clearly;
- use one destination;
- explain what happens after clicking;
- avoid several competing actions;
- do not imply something is free unless confirmed;
- do not request unnecessary personal information.

CLOSING SCRIPT

The closing should:

1. Recap the central takeaway.
2. Clarify the next practical step.
3. Mention the approved CTA.
4. Explain replay or resource access when confirmed.
5. Thank attendees briefly.
6. End the session clearly.

Do not repeat the entire webinar.

Do not introduce a new major topic.

Do not create an unconfirmed future event.

